"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850192","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-01","<p>Serco do not undertake SMI loan processing being contracted solely to provide information to claimants in the form of letters, leaflets and telephone ‘Informed Discussions’. Serco have made 338,000 call attempts, with 275,000 being successful contacts since July 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850192/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T14:42:51.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850192/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850192/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-26","Mortgages: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of Serco’s rate of processing SMI replacement loan applications in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","129760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850193","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>Patient safety remains a key priority of this Government. While there are various tools and mechanisms for reporting pressure ulcers in the National Health Service, the data is not held in the format requested and therefore the most recent figures cannot be published by region.</p><p> </p><p>However, the NHS Safety Thermometer is a point prevalence survey used to record the presence or absence of four harms including pressure ulcers which have developed 72 hours or more following admission or have deteriorated following admission.</p><p> </p><p>Data reports from the NHS Safety Thermometer dating back to August 2012 show a downward trend in incidents of pressure ulcers reported by hospitals from 1.3% in August 2012, to 0.9% in January 2018, the most recent data.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Safety Thermometer Dashboard</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Reported Pressure Ulcers</p></td><td><p>Percentage</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2018</p></td><td><p>0.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2017</p></td><td><p>1.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2016</p></td><td><p>0.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2015</p></td><td><p>1.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2014</p></td><td><p>1.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2013</p></td><td><p>1.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2012</p></td><td><p>1.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source:</p><p><a href="https://www.safetythermometer.nhs.uk/index.php/classic-thermometer/analyse-data-classic/dashboard-classic" target="_blank">https://www.safetythermometer.nhs.uk/index.php/classic-thermometer/analyse-data-classic/dashboard-classic</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850193/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T15:36:54.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850193/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850193/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Pressure Sores","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the (a) number and (b) rate was of hospital acquired pressure ulcers in the NHS in each of the last eight years; and if he will publish the most recent figures by region.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","129761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850194","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-05","<p>The Clean Growth Strategy has a clear focus on the challenges and opportunities involved in decarbonising heat in buildings and industry. We need to reduce the emissions created by heating our homes and businesses as these contribute almost a third of UK emissions.</p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is working in partnership with The Coal Authority to better understand the geothermal mine water resource available across the UK. The Coal Authority has responsibility for managing the mining legacy and has recently assessed there to be over two million gigawatt hours of low carbon heat stored in mine workings across the UK.</p><p>There are a number of ways to utilise this resource: using the heat for heat networks, for agriculture and for energy storage. An example of where this is actively being considered is in Wales, with Bridgend County Borough Council and The Coal Authority working together to explore using this mine heat for a heat network to provide local homes and businesses with low carbon, affordable heating. This can help reduce carbon emissions and contribute to the UK’s energy supply.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850194/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-05T14:51:56.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850194/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850194/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-26","Geothermal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the potential merits of using geothermal mine water to contribute to the UK’s energy supply; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","129762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850195","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Renewable Heat Incentive is a support scheme designed to help bridge the gap between the cost of fossil fuels and renewable and low carbon heat. The Non-domestic RHI currently provides support to both Geothermal Installations and Ground Source Heat Pumps (GSHP). Mine water could potentially be used with either of these technologies. The RHI budget has been set until 2020/21, and there are no current plans to change the support available for these technologies.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850195/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T15:38:16.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850195/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850195/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-26","Geothermal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to offer increased subsidies for the use of geothermal mine water to contribute to the UK’s energy supply.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","129763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850196","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-06","<p>Local authorities have operational responsibility for coroner services and it is for them to make decisions on the need for any particular court.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850196/answer",,,,,"129766","2018-03-06T17:07:42.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850196/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850196/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-26","Coroners: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of the closure of Cardiff Coroner Court on access to justice for residents of the South Wales valleys.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","129764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850197","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-12","<p>The UKSA was the subject of an independent review in 2016. The Cabinet Office’s programme of tailored reviews for its Arms Length Bodies is scheduled to begin shortly, completing in 2019.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850197/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-12T13:49:34.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850197/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850197/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-26","Cabinet Office: Arms Length Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the most recent tailored reviews took place for each of his Department's arms-length bodies.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","129765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850198","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-06","<p>Local authorities have operational responsibility for coroner services and it is for them to make decisions on the need for any particular court.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850198/answer",,,,,"129764","2018-03-06T17:07:42.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850198/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850198/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-26","Coroners: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of the closure of Cardiff Coroner Court on access to justice for people reliant on public transport.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","129766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850199","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-06","<p>This information is not held centrally. The provision of non-emergency patient transport services is a matter for local National Health Service commissioners.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850199/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T14:46:30.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850199/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850199/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many contracts for delivering non-emergency transport services have been (a) cancelled, (b) handed back to the Clinical Commissioning Groups and (c) withdrawn from the provider for poor performance in the last two years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","129767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850200","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>Following completion of a consultation last autumn, NHS Digital announced that recording of data on waiting times from referral for suspected autism to a first appointment and subsequent diagnosis would be collected within the Mental Health Services Data Set from April 2018. In preparation for this, dialogue is taking place between National Health Service mental health trusts which will collate the data and autism diagnostic services about the new requirements. To support those local discussions, the Department has co-ordinated production of a guide which NHS Digital will circulate to trusts in March via their newsletter to provide further clarity. NHS Digital will monitor the quality of the data recorded and submitted from April 2018 and the intention is to publish a first formal report on this data during 2019.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850200/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T14:35:44.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850200/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850200/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Autism: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he has taken to ensure the collection of data to record the waiting times for autism diagnoses in England in version 3 of the Mental Health Services Data Set will begin from April 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","129768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850201","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-06","<p>The oral nicotine product snus was originally banned under Directive 92/41/EEC. This ban was reaffirmed in 2001 and most recently in the Tobacco Products Directive 2014/40/EU, implemented in the United Kingdom by the Tobacco and Related Products Regulations 2016. The Department has received a number of representations concerning snus over recent years. The makers of snus, Swedish Match, have challenged the legality of the ban on snus and this matter is currently before the European Court of Justice; as such, the strength of the evidence for or against the ban is a matter for the Court and the UK awaits the outcome of that case.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850201/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T15:01:27.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850201/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850201/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Oral Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if the government will publish any evidence it has received over the last three years that supports the continuing ban on the oral nicotine product snus.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","129769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850202","Department for Education","false","2018-03-06","<p>The 70 Pupil Referral Units (PRUs) which applied to convert to academy status between January 2013 and January 2018 spanned 45 local authorities (refer to attached Table 1).</p><p> </p><p>The 76 PRUs that converted to alternative provision academies during the same period spanned 47 local authorities (refer to attached Table 2).</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850202/answer","129770 Table 1.docx ; 129770 Table 2.docx","129770 Table 1.docx ; 129770 Table 2.docx","PRUs that applied to convert to an academy 2013-18 ; PRUs that converted to AP academy status 2013-18","PRUs that applied to convert to an academy 2013-18 ; PRUs that converted to AP academy status 2013-18",,"2018-03-06T10:22:33.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850202/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850202/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-26","Pupil Referral Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2018 to Question 125156, on Pupil Referral Units (PRUs), in which local authority areas the (a) 70 PRUs which applied to convert to academy status and (b) 76 PRUs which have converted to alternative provision academies are located.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","129770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850203","Department for Education","false","2018-03-06","<p>Pupil referral units (PRUs) are set up and maintained by local authorities to provide an education to pupils who cannot attend mainstream or special schools.</p><p> </p><p>The data containing the number of PRUs open in each local authority from 2013 to 2017 can be found in the attached table. This table sets out the number of PRUs open in January of each year. This data excludes the number of alternative provision (AP) academies and free schools. To date, there are 117 AP academies and free schools open.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850203/answer","129771 Attachment.xlsx","129771 Attachment.xlsx","Number of PRUs open in January of each year","Number of PRUs open in January of each year",,"2018-03-06T17:51:46.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850203/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850203/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-26","Pupil Referral Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Pupil Referral Units were open in each local authority area in England in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","129771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850204","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-05","<p>The number of technical incidents reported by the Rail Delivery Group on the Great Western Main Line for the Class 800 bi-mode trains since entering passenger service (up to February 3, 2018) is 201.</p><p> </p><p>Technical incidents are those where a problem with the unit or rolling stock leads to a delay of 3 minutes or more; we do not however have the information to determine how many of these technical incidents were essentially minor leading to delays of only a few minutes or were other faults. The figures may additionally be revised to take account of disputes being resolved relating to the responsibility for the delay. This may happen with overhead line faults (Network Rail’s responsibility) being incorrectly described as a rolling stock fault.</p><p> </p><p>New rolling stock often experience teething problems when entering service.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850204/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-05T17:13:06.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850204/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850204/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850204/answer/previousversion/44323","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850204/answer/previousversion/44323",,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-26","Great Western Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, the number of technical incidents registered on bimodal trains on the Great Western Mainline since their inception.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","129772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850205","Department for Education","false","2018-03-06","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Amanda Spielman. I have asked her to write to the hon. Member and a copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850205/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T17:35:15.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850205/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850205/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-26","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 5 February 2018 to Question 125158, on teachers: training, what (a) criteria and (b) assessment tools Ofsted uses to judge the quality of the (i) training, (ii)  leadership and management and (iii) ability to meet the framework of core content of an initial teacher training partnership.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","129773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850206","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>With respect to the missions referred to in the response to PQ128168 (Naval Force for Somalia; Training Mission in Mali; Force Althea in Bosnia and Herzegovina; Naval Force in the Mediterranean; Training Mission in Somalia; Monitoring Mission in Georgia; Advisory Mission in Ukraine; EU Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo; Kosovo Specialist Chambers and Specialist Prosecutor's Office in the Netherlands; and the Capacity Building Mission in Mali), there have been no Orders in Council made under s.4B(2) of the International Organisations Act 1968.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850206/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T13:13:22.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850206/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850206/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-26","EU Defence Policy: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2018 to Question 128168, on EU Defence Policy: British Nationals Abroad, if he will list the Orders In Council made under s.4B(2) of the International Organisations Act 1968 in respect of each of the organisations named in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Anna McMorrin","Cardiff North","Anna McMorrin","129774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850207","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-02","<p>​Indonesian President Joko Widodo made a commitment in May 2015 that foreign journalists would be allowed to visit Papua and West Papua. Nevertheless, we continue to receive reports that journalists face difficulties in securing visas and restrictions on free reporting. In January of this year, Lord Ahmad raised his concern on this issue with the Indonesian Ambassador to London and we submitted an advanced question to Indonesia on this ahead of their Universal Periodic Review at the Human Rights Council in May 2017.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850207/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T14:05:28.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850207/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850207/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-26","Papua: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Indonesian Government on its decision to restrict the international media presence in West Papua.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","129775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850208","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-02","<p>The Government follows the situation in Papua closely and regularly presses the Indonesian authorities to address legitimate concerns relating to human rights and restrictions on freedom of expression. We assess this to be the most effective method to raise our concerns. We are pleased that the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR) has been invited to visit Papua soon.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850208/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T14:07:00.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850208/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850208/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-26","Papua: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to discuss human rights violations in West Papua at the UN Human Rights Council in March 2018.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","129776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850209","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-02","<p>The Government follows the situation in Papua closely and regularly presses the Indonesian authorities to address legitimate concerns relating to human rights and restrictions on freedom of expression.</p><p>In January, Lord Ahmad met the Indonesian ambassador to London and raised reports of restricted access to Papua for journalists and investigations into alleged human rights abuses by security forces there. Our Ambassador to Indonesia, Moazzam Malik visited the province in November last year as part of his regular programme of travel around Indonesia. During the visit, he met local government officials, civil society groups, businesses and local communities and discussed human rights.</p><p> </p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850209/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T14:10:21.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850209/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850209/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-26","Papua: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the human rights situation in West Papua.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","129777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850210","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-02","<p>No. The Indonesian provinces of Papua and West Papua are not one of the 17 non-self-governing territories covered by the UN decolonisation committee and therefore fall outside of the committee's mandate.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850210/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T14:12:44.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850210/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850210/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-26","Papua: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to make representations to the UN Decolonisation Committee on the situation in West Papua; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","129778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850211","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-16","<p>The Childcare Implementation Taskforce focused on cross-government readiness for the rollout of a coherent and effective childcare offer to support parents to work. From 2017, we began rolling out 30 hours of free childcare to working families of 3 and 4 year olds; support with 20% of childcare costs (worth up to £2,000 per child per year) for children under 12 through Tax-Free Childcare; and up to 85% support with childcare costs in Universal Credit. The Government remains absolutely focused on ensuring that all eligible parents can access these services as efficiently as possible.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850211/answer",,,,,"129780","2018-03-16T14:23:32.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850211/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850211/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-26","Childcare Implementation Taskforce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the reason is for the omission of the Childcare Implementation Taskforce from the list of Cabinet Committees and Implementation Taskforces published on gov.uk.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850212","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-16","<p>The Childcare Implementation Taskforce focused on cross-government readiness for the rollout of a coherent and effective childcare offer to support parents to work. From 2017, we began rolling out 30 hours of free childcare to working families of 3 and 4 year olds; support with 20% of childcare costs (worth up to £2,000 per child per year) for children under 12 through Tax-Free Childcare; and up to 85% support with childcare costs in Universal Credit. The Government remains absolutely focused on ensuring that all eligible parents can access these services as efficiently as possible.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850212/answer",,,,,"129779","2018-03-16T14:23:32.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850212/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850212/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-26","Childcare Implementation Taskforce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Childcare Implementation Taskforce has been disbanded.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850213","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-08","<p>The Government remains committed to estate regeneration and reaffirmed this commitment by announcing an additional £400 million at Autumn Budget.</p><p>Below is a table that outlines the funding (net budget) allocated to the Estate Regeneration Programme from 2018/19 onwards. This is comprised of the remaining balance of previously allocated funding plus £400 million made available to the Department as part of the Autumn Budget settlement.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Estate Regeneration</strong> <strong>Programme</strong></p></td><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Capital (Financial Transactions) Net Budget</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>£'000</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018/19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019/20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020/21</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2021/22</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2022/23</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Loans</p></td><td><p>93,700</p></td><td><p>95,800</p></td><td><p>109,400</p></td><td><p>100,000</p></td><td><p>498,900</p></td><td><p>498,900</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850213/answer",,,,,"129931","2018-03-08T11:40:41.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850213/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850213/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850213/answer/previousversion/44311","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850213/answer/previousversion/44311",,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-26","Housing Estates: Regeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's explanatory memorandum to its Supplementary Estimate 2017-18, how much funding remains allocated to estate regeneration in each financial year from 2018-19.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","129781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850214","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-08","<p>Surrendered and reallocated funding are as set out in my Department’s 2017/18 supplementary estimates. This compares with underspends including £122 million for “Building prosperous communities, promoting regeneration and tackling deprivation” and £144 million for “Improving the supply and quality of housing” in 2009/10 when the Rt Hon Member had responsibility for housing.</p><p>There remains funding for the Starter Home Land Fund which we are reviewing following the announcement of a new £1.1 billion land assembly fund in the Autumn Budget. This change in the starter homes budget will reduce the number of starter homes expected to be delivered through funding compared to the original estimates. But, as the Housing White Paper made clear, the Government’s aim is to ensure young people have a range of housing products they can choose from to support their aspiration into homeownership, including Help to Buy, shared ownership and rent to buy, as well as discount market sales like starter homes. The additional funding for the affordable housing programme is expected to deliver at least 25,000 additional affordable homes, including homes at a social rent.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850214/answer",,,,,"129934","2018-03-08T16:15:17.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850214/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850214/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850214/answer/previousversion/44314","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850214/answer/previousversion/44314",,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-26","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's explanatory memorandum to its Supplementary Estimate 2017-18, how much funding remains allocated to starter homes in each financial  year from 2018-19.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","129782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850215","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-08","<p>The Build to Rent Fund was closed to new applications in 2016. At the 2017/18 Supplementary Estimate, the following budget profile was agreed in order to provide for loans to be drawn down under existing loan agreements under the Fund:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018-19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019-20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020-21</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Grand Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Gross budget</strong></p></td><td><p>150,000</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>150,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Prospective developers of housing built for rent may also apply to my Department for support under the Home Building Fund, which became operational in 2016.</p><p>In addition, our private rented sector housing debt guarantee scheme has approved approximately £1.5 billion of transactions. Government funding and guarantees are just one source of investment for the Build to Rent sector. Knight Frank, a real estate consultancy firm, estimated that £25 billion had been invested in the sector in total (UK figure) as of 2017.</p><p>The Build to Rent Fund is a loan fund made available in order to support and encourage investment in the build-to-rent housing sector. The fund received more financial transaction income in 17/18 than expected. In line with good financial management of public funds, this allowed the Department to return £52 million of funding back to HMT. The surrender has no impact on the delivery of affordable housing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850215/answer",,,,,"129930","2018-03-08T16:24:33.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850215/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850215/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-26","Private Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's explanatory memorandum to its Supplementary Estimate 2017-18, how much funding remains allocated to build-to-rent in each financial year from 2018-19.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","129783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850216","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-08","<p>The Government remains committed to building more affordable housing. Last October we announced an additional £2 billion funding for affordable housing, increasing the Affordable Homes Programme budget to over £9 billion between 2016-17 and 2020-21.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850216/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-08T16:16:55.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850216/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850216/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-26","Affordable Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's explanatory memorandum to its Supplementary Estimate 2017-18, how much funding remains allocated to affordable housing in each financial year from 2018-19.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","129784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850217","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>Public sector procurers are required to seek value for money through fair and open competition and in line with our current international obligations.</p><p>The Government wants UK companies to be successful in public procurement, and we are seeking to ensure the huge purchasing power of government supports the task of boosting growth, and enables us to actively shape the UK market for the long term.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850217/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T10:44:55.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850217/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850217/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-26","Government Departments: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to encourage UK SMEs and other UK suppliers to win cloud-hosting contracts.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","129785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850218","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-07","<p>In answer to part (a), Cabinet Office does not hold the requested information.</p><p>In answer to part (b) UK SMEs have been awarded the following cloud hosting contracts by value over the last 3 calendar years (2015 to 2017 inclusive):</p><p> </p><p>Cabinet Office cloud-hosting buying with UK SMEs only</p><p>(based on data that has been matched with Crown Commercial Service spend data)</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Hosting only</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Rounded</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£1,702,671</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£3,703,496</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£4,326,741</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total cloud hosting</p></td><td><p>£9.7M</p></td><td><p>£9,732,908</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£496,667</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£1,853,388</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£1,420,935</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SME cloud hosting</p></td><td><p>£3.8M</p></td><td><p>£3,770,990</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>29.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>50.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>32.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% SME</p></td><td><p>39%</p></td><td><p>38.7%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850218/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-07T10:40:20.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850218/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850218/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-26","Cabinet Office: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of his Department’s cloud-hosting contracts have been awarded to (a) hyperscale cloud providers and (b) UK SMEs; and what the value of those contracts was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","129786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850219","Home Office","false","2018-03-12","<p>Since 2016, the Secretary of State for the Home Department has not used the power to impose a restriction notice under section 19(2)(a) of the Inquiries Act 2005.</p><p>Under Section 19(2)(b) of the Inquiries Act 2005, a restriction order may be imposed by the Chairman during the course of an Inquiry. The publication of a restriction order is a matter for the issuing Inquiry; independent from Government.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850219/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-12T18:05:42.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850219/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850219/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-26","Inquiries: Rules of Procedure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the number of restriction (a) notices and (b) orders her Department has issued to restrict inquiries under (i) section 19(1)(a) and (ii) section 19(1)(b) of the Inquiries Act 2005 since 2016 (A) in total and (B) for the Undercover Policing Inquiry.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850220","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-01","<p>It is our policy to award contracts on the basis of value for money, whilst doing everything we can to encourage UK suppliers, and UK SME's in particular, to win business. This is achieved through competitive tender in accordance with public procurement legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The department has seven cloud-hosting contracts, of which five have been awarded to UK SMEs and zero have been awarded to hyperscale providers. The total value of the contracts awarded to SMEs is £162,256.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850220/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T14:45:24.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850220/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850220/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-26","Treasury: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many and what proportion of his Department’s cloud-hosting contracts have been awarded to (a) hyperscale cloud providers and (b) UK SMEs; and what the value of those contracts was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","129788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850221","Home Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Home Office has a number of cloud hosting contracts, with a variety of service providers.</p><p>It is our policy to award contracts on the basis of value for money, whilst doing everything we can to encourage UK suppliers, and UK SME's in particular, to win business. This is achieved through competitive tender in accordance with public procurement legislation.The Home Office actively encourages SMEs to bid for Government contracts and where applicable include relevant clauses in our terms and conditions and tender process to encourage UK suppliers to use SMEs within their supply chain.</p><p>The Home Office has a number of cloud hosting contracts with hypercloud providers, such as Amazon Web Services, Oracle Fusion and Microsoft Azure, as well as contracts with Vodafone, DXC, SCC and UKCloud. The Department has a number of smaller hosting contracts, with a wide variety of UK-based and we utilise the services of other hosting providers through our extended service integrator supplier base.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850221/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T17:18:13.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850221/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850221/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-26","Home Office: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many and what proportion of her Department’s cloud-hosting contracts have been awarded to (a) hyperscale cloud providers and (b) UK SMEs; and what the value of those contracts was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","129789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850222","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has placed one contract with UK Cloud Ltd, who are considered an SME. The FCO have zero Hyperscale contracts.</p><p>The FCO Overall expenditure the last three Financial years is as follows:</p><p>FY 14/15: £36,863</p><p>FY 15-16: £152,093</p><p>FY 16-17: £231,012</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850222/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T12:47:46.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850222/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850222/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-26","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many and what proportion of his Department’s cloud-hosting contracts have been awarded to (a) hyperscale cloud providers and (b) UK SMEs; and what the value of those contracts was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","129790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850223","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-05","<p>HM Land Registry records the number of freehold and leasehold titles registered. A registered title does not always equate one to one with an individual property.</p><p> </p><p>(i) For London, there are (a) 3,077,299 mortgages, (b) 1,368,992 leasehold titles and a total of 3,262,166 freehold and leasehold titles registered with HM Land Registry.</p><p> </p><p>(ii) For Hampstead and Kilburn, there are (a) 27,508 mortgages, (b) 35,241 leasehold titles and a total of 55,648 freehold and leasehold titles registered with HM Land Registry.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850223/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-05T14:36:27.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850223/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850223/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-26","Land Registry: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many (a) mortgages, (b) leaseholds and (c) properties overall are registered with the Land Registry in (i) London and (ii) Hampstead and Kilburn constituency.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850224","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-05","<p>HM Land Registry publishes information on its fees and charges on its website at GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Nationally for 2015/2016 HM Land Registry received £290,389,000 in statutory fee income and £4,983,000 in non-statutory fee income.</p><p> </p><p>Nationally for 2016/2017 HM Land Registry received £305,858,000 in statutory fee income and £5,567,000 in non-statutory fee income.</p><p> </p><p>Fee data is not held at regional or constituency level and obtaining that would be at disproportionate cost.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850224/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-05T17:27:19.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850224/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850224/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-26","Land Registry: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish the amount charged by the Land Registry in fees for each of the (a) statutory and (b) non-statutory functions it fulfils in each financial year since 2016; and how much was raised in fees (i) nationally, (ii) from registrations in London and (iii) from registrations in Hampstead and Kilburn constituency in each financial year since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850225","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-05","<p>Estimates of the number of jobs paid below NMW/NLW are available in Chart 3 on page 10 of the 2017 Government evidence to the LPC report- <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630197/nmw-nlw-lpc-evidence-compliance-enforcement-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630197/nmw-nlw-lpc-evidence-compliance-enforcement-2017.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government will publish new evidence to the Low Pay Commission containing ASHE 2017 estimates of jobs below minimum wage rates and enforcement stats for 2017/18 later this year.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850225/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-05T14:57:26.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850225/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850225/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-26","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, to publish the latest estimates made by HM Revenue and Customs on the (a) number and (b) proportion of workers in (i) the adult care sector and (ii) each other sector who were paid below the level of the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850226","Home Office","false","2018-05-02","<p>The number of outgoing mutual legal assistance requests for money laundering offences transmitted via the Home Office was 83 in 2016 and 58 in the first half of 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The data does not include requests transmitted directly under the EU’s Council Framework Decisions 2003/577/JHA (Freezing Orders) and 2006/783/JHA (Confiscation Orders). Outgoing requests for restraint or confiscation made under the 2003 and 2006 EU Framework decisions are sent by the CPS directly to the relevant EU Member State.</p><p> </p><p>Please note that these figures are taken from local management information, and have not been quality assured to the level of published National Statistics. As such they should be treated as provisional and therefore subject to change.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850226/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-02T10:44:49.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850226/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850226/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-26","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the number of requests for mutual legal assistance that have been made to foreign jurisdictions to recover criminal assets laundered abroad since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850227","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-06","<p>The number of offenders found guilty at all courts for offences related to refusal to take an assistance dog in a taxi or private hire vehicle, in England and Wales, from 2011 to 2016, can be viewed in the table. Prior to 2011, these offences were recorded as part of a miscellaneous offence group, which cannot be separately analysed until 2011.</p><p> </p><p>Court proceedings data for 2017 are planned for publication in May 2018.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850227/answer","PQ 129795 table.xlsx","PQ 129795 table.xlsx","Table","Table",,"2018-03-06T17:07:25.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850227/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850227/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-26","Taxis: Assistance Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were convicted under section 168 of the Equality Act 2010 for refusing to take an assistance dog in a taxi or private hire vehicle since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850228","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-05","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy published a summary of responses to the consultation on Property ownership and public contracting by overseas companies: improving transparency on 5 April 2017. On the same day, the Department published a call for evidence on an Overseas companies and other legal entities beneficial ownership register. The Government response to the call for evidence will be published shortly. On 24 January this year the Government issued a written ministerial statement confirming the timetable for implementation of this register. The Government will publish a draft Bill before the summer recess this year. We intend to introduce the Bill to Parliament early in the second session. Following Royal Assent and the making of secondary legislation to implement some of the technical details, the register will be operational in 2021.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850228/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-05T14:34:19.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850228/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850228/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-26","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the consultation Property ownership and public contracting by overseas companies: improving transparency, published by his Department on 4 March 2016, what steps his Department has taken following the results of that consultation.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850229","Attorney General","false","2018-03-12","<p>Details of funding and staffing for the Serious Fraud Office covering the years 2015-16 and 2016-17 can be found in the respective SFO Annual Report and Accounts. These are laid before the House each year and deposited in the Library of the House. These can also be accessed online at: <a href="http://www.sfo.gov.uk/publications/corporate-information/annual-reports-accounts/" target="_blank">www.sfo.gov.uk/publications/corporate-information/annual-reports-accounts/</a>. Details for financial year 2017-2018 are due to published later this year once the 2017-18 Annual Report and Accounts have been prepared and then audited by the National Audit Office.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850229/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-12T16:43:27.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850229/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850229/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-02-26","Serious Fraud Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much funding his Department allocated to the Serious Fraud Office in each year since 2016; and how many staff the Serious Fraud Office employed in each year since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850230","Attorney General","false","2018-03-12","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service’s (CPS) has allocated £9,536,522 to its central Proceeds of Crime Unit in 2016/17. This does not include work carried out in CPS Areas. An average 127.7 full time equivalent staff were in post in the Proceeds of Crime Unit during 2016/17</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850230/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-12T16:43:36.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850230/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850230/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-02-26","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, if he will publish (a) the amount of money he has allocated to and (b) how many full-time equivalent staff were employed by CPS Proceeds of Crime in each year since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850231","Home Office","false","2018-03-02","<p>The first Asset Recovery Statistical Bulletin was issued in September 2017 and will be published on an annual basis. It included the gross annual confiscation receipts.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850231/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T15:08:17.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850231/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850231/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-26","Confiscation Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many confiscation orders have been issued under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 since 2016; what the value of assets subject to restraint orders under that Act since 2016 were; and if she will publish the gross confiscation receipts year since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850232","Attorney General","false","2018-03-12","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not get direct referrals from the Office of Financial Sanctions Implementation.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850232/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-12T16:43:46.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850232/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850232/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-02-26","Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many referrals the Crown Prosecution Service has received from the Office of Financial Sanctions Implementation on the breach of financial sanctions in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850233","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) is the lead Government Department for the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). The FCO pays the UK assessed contribution to the OECD budget, which includes work on tax.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016 HM Treasury allocated an additional voluntary contribution of €500,000 to the OECD for work on their Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS) Project. HM Treasury fully supports the OECD’s work on tax matters, including through BEPS and the Common Reporting Standard (CRS).</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850233/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T17:47:18.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850233/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850233/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-26","Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much money his Department has allocated since 2016 to the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development to ensure profits are taxed where economic activities are performed.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850234","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-01","<p>The UK is committed to automatic exchange of offshore account data with 102 jurisdictions under multilateral and bilateral arrangements.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850234/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T14:59:09.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850234/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850234/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-26","Tax Avoidance: International Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many countries the UK has made arrangements with to provide automatic offshore account and trust data since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850235","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-06","<p>HMRC has provided two auditors to Tax Inspectors Without Borders since 2016.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850235/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T16:12:38.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850235/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850235/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-26","Taxation: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many tax auditors HMRC has provided to Tax Inspectors Without Borders since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850236","Department for Education","false","2018-03-06","<p>As of 27 February 2018, there are 391 open free schools, 35 studio schools and 49 university technical colleges (UTCs), which will provide over 256,000 places when at capacity<strong>.</strong></p><p>Since 2010, eight free schools, seven UTCs and 16 studio schools have closed. The primary objective of the Department when making a decision to close a school is to ensure the best possible educational outcomes for pupils and to secure value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p>The list attached has details on how the sites for those schools have since been used. The Department’s published accounts explain any assets that were written off because they could not be reused or recovered.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850236/answer","129804 - Attachment.docx","129804 - Attachment.docx","Site Information Regarding School Closures","Site Information Regarding School Closures",,"2018-03-06T17:58:08.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850236/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850236/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-26","Academies: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which (a) free schools, (b) studio schools (c) and university technical colleges have closed since 2010; what the cost to the public purse was of each of those closures; and what each of those sites has been used for since each school closure.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","129804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850237","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-06","<p>The information requested on the amount of revenue lost as a result of (a) tax evasion and (b) the hidden economy for the tax year 2015-16 is available in Chapter 1 of the Measuring Tax Gaps 2017 report, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/655097/HMRC-measuring-tax-gaps-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/655097/HMRC-measuring-tax-gaps-2017.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Information on tax year 2016-17 and 2017-18 will be published in due course by HM Revenue and Customs as part of the Measuring Tax Gaps series.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850237/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T16:32:13.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850237/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850237/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-26","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the amount of revenue for the public purse which was lost as a result of (a) tax evasion and (b) the hidden economy in each year since 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850238","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-06","<p>HMRC has allocated £1.8 million from the Overseas Development Assistance element of its budget to support developing countries through various projects such as Capacity Building Unit across a three year period from 2015/16 to 2017/18.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850238/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-06T16:00:35.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850238/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850238/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-26","Taxation: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding his Department has allocated to HMRC's dedicated tax avoidance and evasion team for developing countries since Autumn Statement 2014.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","129806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850239","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>In March 2015 the Government restated its longstanding policy commitment to pay 80% of undisputed and valid invoices within 5 days with the remainder paid within 30 days.</p><p>Public sector buyers must publish annually on their payment performance. We do not hold centrally the performance data for 2017. However, data published in 2015-16 shows that by the final quarter all major departments, apart from one (at 76%), were meeting their 5 days target and that all departments were paying at least 96% of their invoices within the 30 day target, with several departments achieving 100%.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850239/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T10:49:59.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850239/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850239/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-26","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the First Secretary of State, what the target time is for the Government to make payments to small and medium-sized enterprises; and (a) how many and (b) what percentage of payments by the Government met that target in 2017.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","129807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850240","Department for Education","false","2018-03-06","<p>Music is a statutory subject in the national curriculum for 5-14 year olds attending maintained schools. Academies and free schools do not have to follow the national curriculum, but they are required to teach a broad and balanced curriculum. It is up to individual schools to decide whether to appoint specialist music teachers.</p><p>The Government is investing £300 million of ring-fenced funding in music education hubs in 2016/20. This will ensure that all children, regardless of background, have access to a high quality music education. Hubs ensure that all pupils have the opportunity to learn an instrument, sing and perform regularly and have access to clear routes of progression. The funding formula for allocating funding between music education hubs includes a weighting for disadvantaged pupils.</p><p>As well as funding music education hubs, the Government also supports the Music for Youth festival series, National Youth Music Organisations such as the National Youth Orchestra, and the Music and Dance Scheme for exceptionally talented young musicians and dancers.</p><p>The Government has not undertaken any enquiries to ascertain whether any schools have removed music from the curriculum in the last five years. However, data on the hours of music taught by teachers in Years 7 to 13 in state funded secondary schools shows that this was 2.4 per cent of total teaching time in 2010, compared with 2.3 per cent in 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850240/answer",,,,,"129809 ; 129810 ; 129811 ; 129812","2018-03-06T17:45:41.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850240/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850240/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-26","Music: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the Government’s policy is on the provision of music lessons in schools.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","129808"
