"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846950","Department for Education","false","2018-03-02","<p>44 providers allocated funding from the Adult Education Budget received an inadequate outcome following their latest financial health assessment by the Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA).</p><p>The ESFA does not have direct relationships with subcontractors and does not visit them. The contractor is responsible for all the actions of its subcontractors connected to or arising out of the delivery of the services, which it sub-contracts.</p><p>Since 1 April 2017, the ESFA has received a total of 33 reports covering allegations of irregular financial and/or delivery activity. This includes sub-contracted provision.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846950/answer",,,,,"129122 ; 129123","2018-03-02T14:25:53.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846950/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846950/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-22","Adult Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many reports his Department has received of irregular (a) financial and (b) delivery activity at providers, including sub-contracted provision, that received Adult Education Budget funding in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","129124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846951","Department for Education","false","2018-02-27","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846951/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:09:38.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846951/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846951/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-22","Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many on-site visits Education and Skills Funding Agency staff have made to (a) Multi Academy Trusts and (b) other schools by region in each of the past 3 years.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","129125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846952","Department for Education","false","2018-02-27","<p>Academy trust accountability is founded on a clear framework communicated and regulated by the Education and Skills Funding Agency. As a condition of their funding agreement, all academy trusts are required to prepare annual accounts, independently audited by a statutory auditor.</p><p>As part of the audit process, the independent auditor undertakes a regularity review to identify instances of material irregularity and non-compliance with the accountability framework. The auditor’s ‘Report on Regularity’ is included in every trust’s annual accounts that are published on each trust’s website and filed with Companies House.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of cases where auditors did not raise any concerns in their regularity reports and those where auditors noted matters of material irregularity and non-compliance for each of the three academy years 2013 to 2014, 2014 to 2015 and 2015 to 2016. Figures for 2016 to 2017 will be published in Academies Sector Annual Report and Accounts in October 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Any regional breakdown of this national analysis could be potentially misleading given that many multi-academy trusts span regional boundaries.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Auditor's Regularity Report</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>No material irregularity or non-compliance</p></td><td><p>2,554</p></td><td><p>2,782</p></td><td><p>2,865</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Material irregularity or non-compliance reported</p></td><td><p>136</p></td><td><p>119</p></td><td><p>136</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total Academy Trusts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,690</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,901</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,001</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage with reported non-compliance</p></td><td><p>5.1%</p></td><td><p>4.1%</p></td><td><p>4.5%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846952/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:08:02.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846952/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846952/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-22","Academies: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many reports his Department has received of irregular financial activity at academy schools, by region, in each of the last.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","129126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846953","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-02","<p>My Department is carefully considering the recommendations made by the Review of Full Time Social Action by Young People, including the recommendation relating to the National Citizen Service. The Government will issue its response in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846953/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T12:33:09.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846953/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846953/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-02-22","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Independent review of Full-Time Social Action, published in January 2018, what assessment his Department has made of potential merits of youth full-time social action in relation to the National Citizen Service.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","129127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846954","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-27","<p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union has met with the Mayor of London several times since the Referendum. At their last meeting on the 11 September 2017 they discussed key issues relevant to London with regard to the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government is committed to positive and productive engagement with the Mayor of London and will continue to work closely with him to understand the potential impact and opportunities presented by the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p>","Fareham","Suella Fernandes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846954/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T15:45:07.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846954/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846954/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-02-22","Brexit: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with (a) The Mayor of London and (b) Members of the GLA on the effect on London of the Greater London Authority report, Preparing for Brexit, published in January 2018.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","129128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846955","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-01","<p>Treasury ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. This includes regular meetings with regulators to discuss relevant issues, including ATM provision.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846955/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T13:16:05.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846955/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846955/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-22","LINK Interchange Network: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his Department has had with (a) LINK and (b) the Payment Systems Regulator on guarantees for protections proposed in LINK’s Financial Inclusion Programme.","false","Biography information for Simon Hoare","North Dorset","Simon Hoare","129129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846956","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Government recognises that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK. Government will continue to engage with industry to ensure that widespread free access is maintained.</p><p> </p><p>The Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which Government set up as an independent regulator in 2015 with a statutory objective to ensure that the UK’s payment systems work in the interests of their users, is monitoring developments within ATM provision, and is conducting ongoing work on the impact that changes may have. The PSR has recently published a summary of their work to date, which can be found at https://www.psr.org.uk/psr-focus/the-UK-ATM-network.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has committed to using its powers to act should any of the firms it regulates behave in a way that conflicts with its statutory objectives.</p><p> </p><p>LINK, the main scheme behind the UK’s ATM network, has assured us and the PSR that industry is committed to maintaining an extensive network of free-to-use cash machines, and to ensuring that the present geographical spread of ATMs is maintained. LINK has announced plans to bolster its Financial Inclusion Programme, which ensures the provision of ATMs in certain areas where demand would not otherwise make one viable. LINK has also committed to protecting all free-to-use ATMs which are a kilometre or more from the next nearest free-to-use ATM, and to ensuring that any community that loses ATM access because of a branch closure has a free ATM provided.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, LINK will set up publicly available monitoring on its website of every area of the country showing free ATM availability, and highlight any areas where free ATM availability is lost.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846956/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T13:09:14.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846956/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846956/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-22","Cash Dispensing: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) long-term and (b) short-term effect of LINK’s proposals to reduce the interchange fee on the free-to-use ATM network; and what estimate has been made of the number of ATMs that will be affected by that reduction.","false","Biography information for Simon Hoare","North Dorset","Simon Hoare","129130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846957","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-02","<p>This information is available on the Bank of England website at: <a href="https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/banknote" target="_blank">https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/statistics/banknote</a></p><p>Summary tables have been reproduced below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Number of banknotes produced (m)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>1369</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>1290</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>994</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>1310</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>952</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>843</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>674</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>912</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Number of banknotes in circulation (£m)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2576.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2667.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2833.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2993.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>3070.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>3238.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>3420.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>3662.9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846957/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T13:13:55.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846957/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846957/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-22","Bank Notes","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many bank notes were (a) printed and (b) in circulation each year between 2010 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Simon Hoare","North Dorset","Simon Hoare","129131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846958","Department for Education","false","2018-02-27","<p>The government is currently considering the recommendations of the National Fostering Stocktake report, alongside those made by the Education Select Committee. Our response to both reports will be published in spring 2018.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846958/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:30:55.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846958/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846958/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-22","Foster Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the Government plans to respond to the recommendations of the report on the National Fostering Stocktake, published in February 2018.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","129132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846959","Home Office","false","2018-03-12","<p>Drugs are illegal and there is scientific and medical evidence that they are harmful to health and society. The possession of any amount of a controlled drug is a criminal offence and the supply of a controlled drug (with intent to supply to others) is an even more serious offence. No illegal drug-taking can be assumed to be safe and there is no safe way to take them.</p><p>The Government’s approach remains clear: we must prevent illicit drug use in our communities and help those dependent to recover, while ensuring that our drugs laws are enforced. While operational decisions are a matter for Chief Constables, the Government and the public expect the police to enforce the law.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846959/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-12T18:34:39.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846959/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846959/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-22","Drugs: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Office, with reference to the report, Reducing Crime and Preventing Harm: West Midlands Drug Policy Recommendations, published in February 2018, whether she plans to bring forward proposals for the introduction of city centre drug testing facilities at night time economy venues.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","129133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846960","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-01","<p>The energy industries directly employed 178,000 people in 2016. Further jobs are supported indirectly, for example, an estimated 152,000 were employed in support of UK oil and gas extraction, while the ONS separately estimates that the low carbon electricity sector employed 40,500 in the supply chain.</p><p> </p><p>Source: Table 2 of UK Energy in Brief <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/631147/UK_Energy_in_Brief_2017_dataset.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/631147/UK_Energy_in_Brief_2017_dataset.xls</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846960/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T15:19:42.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846960/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846960/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-22","Energy: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many people are employed in the energy sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","129134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846961","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-27","<p>The government always considers the compatibility of tax policy measures with different domestic and international legal obligations, as part of an assessment of their merits and feasibility.</p><p>That is particularly important for tax measures that are targeted at specific industries or narrow groups of companies.</p><p>There would also be a need to consider the wider challenges with a windfall tax that discriminates against PFI companies.</p><p>That includes the impact on investor confidence, as well as the obligation that the government or procuring authorities would face to provide compensation where contracts include an anti-discrimination clause.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846961/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T15:50:23.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846961/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846961/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-22","Private Finance Initiative: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has taken legal advice on the principle of a windfall tax on PFI companies.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","129135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846962","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-27","<p>The publication of Work and Heath Programme data is still at the planning stage and current plans are for official statistics to be produced in the autumn of 2018. The frequency of the statistics will be established as part of the planning process.</p><p>Significant progress has been made in the delivery of the Work and Health Programme which will be fully available across England and Wales by March 2018. The Programme will provide support for around 245,000 disabled people, priority groups and the long term unemployed, with the objective to support individuals within these groups to find sustained employment.</p><p>This is a significant step to help thousands of disabled people across England and Wales get the support they need to move away from benefits and find lasting work and underlines the Government commitment to improving employment outcomes for disabled people. We have committed to a clear and time-bound goal to see 1 million more disabled people into work over the next 10 years with the Work and Health Programme contributing towards this aim.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846962/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T16:35:24.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846962/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846962/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-22","Work and Health Programme: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when her Department plans to first publish data on Work and Health Programme outcomes; and how often her Department plans to do so subsequently.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","129136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846963","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-02","<p>The Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill is clear that Ofgem must have regard to the need to ensure that holders of supply licences who operate efficiently are able to finance activities authorised by the licence. It would be for the independent regulator, Ofgem, to make its assessment of efficient operations. Ofgem is not required to have regard to investment projects that are outside the scope of the activities authorised by the supply licence.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846963/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T11:04:41.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846963/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846963/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-22","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill on future investment by UK energy companies in (a) renewable energy, (b) nuclear power generation, (c) gas-fired power plants and (d) battery storage; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","129137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846964","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-27","<p>The Youth Obligation was introduced on 26 April 2017 to provide intensive support for 18-21 year olds making a new claim to Universal Credit Full Service. We are rolling out the Youth Obligation in line with the roll-out schedule for Universal Credit Full Service, and as this progresses, we are considering our evaluation strategy.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846964/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T10:42:34.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846964/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846964/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-22","Universal Credit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when her Department plans to publish its review of the Youth Obligation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","129138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846965","Scotland Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>I am in regular contact with NFU Scotland on a wide range of issues affecting the agriculture sector in Scotland, including the employment of EU agricultural workers, and am due to meet them again in the coming weeks.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846965/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T11:54:00.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846965/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846965/answer",,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-02-22","Agriculture: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with NFU Scotland on the employment of EU agricultural workers after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","129139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846966","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Worsley and Eccles South (Barbara Keeley) on 26 February 2018 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=128962" target="_blank">128962</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846966/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:34:19.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846966/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846966/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Social Services: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate his Department has made of the total sleep-in back pay liability for care providers in the Hove constituency.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","129140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846967","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-27","<p>DFID is in regular discussion with other UK Government Departments about transparency and is supporting them to improve the Official Development Assistance (ODA) data they currently publish, through the provision of guidance, tailored training events and advice on technical issues.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846967/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:49:36.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846967/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846967/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-02-22","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to improve the transparency of Official Development Assistance that is spent by other Government Departments.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","129141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846968","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Private Finance Initiative (PFI) contract between the Royal Liverpool and Broadgreen University Hospitals NHS Trust and the PFI Project Company is still in place, which means that the Company is still contractually obliged to manage the project and find a construction firm or subcontractor who can continue the building work.</p><p> </p><p>The Royal Liverpool Hospital scheme is very well advanced. The PFI Project Company is continuing its discussions with PwC (on behalf of the official receiver), their lenders and with other service and construction companies to assess how best to continue delivering the contract.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846968/answer",,,,,"129143","2018-03-01T14:53:17.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846968/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846968/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Royal Liverpool University Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the timetable is for a new contract to be agreed for the completion of the new Royal Liverpool University Hospital; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","129142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846969","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Private Finance Initiative (PFI) contract between the Royal Liverpool and Broadgreen University Hospitals NHS Trust and the PFI Project Company is still in place, which means that the Company is still contractually obliged to manage the project and find a construction firm or subcontractor who can continue the building work.</p><p> </p><p>The Royal Liverpool Hospital scheme is very well advanced. The PFI Project Company is continuing its discussions with PwC (on behalf of the official receiver), their lenders and with other service and construction companies to assess how best to continue delivering the contract.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846969/answer",,,,,"129142","2018-03-01T14:53:17.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846969/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846969/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the liquidation of Carillion on the completion of building work at the Royal Liverpool University Hospital; and will he make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","129143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846970","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>The number of medical cases dealt with by the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) has increased from 656,000 in 2013/14 to 741,000 in 2017/18.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Since April 2013, the number of staff in the DVLA’s medical section has increased by 218. This includes an increase in the number of doctors employed from 22 to 36. Ten nurses were also recruited for the first time in 2017. The doctors and nurses employed by the DVLA deal with the most complex medical cases.</p><p> </p><p>During this time, DVLA has also made significant changes to IT systems and processes to improve customer service and increase efficiency. This includes the online service introduced in October 2016 to allow customers to notify the DVLA of a medical condition or renew a driving licence previously issued following a medical condition.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846970/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T11:54:08.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846970/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846970/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of whether the work load of the DVLA's medical section has increased in the last five years; and how many extra staff have been hired in that section in that same period.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","129144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846971","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>Information is not held on the number of people who fail to comply with their legal obligation to notify the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) of a medical condition that may affect their fitness to drive.</p><p>The UK’s roads are among the safest in the world and there is no evidence to suggest that there is a widespread road safety issue related to drivers who may be driving inappropriately due to a prescribed medical condition.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846971/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T09:48:23.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846971/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846971/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of people who did not inform the DVLA of medical conditions as required in each the last five years; and what assessment he has made of the reasons people do not so inform the DVLA.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","129145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846972","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>Information about the number of people prosecuted for failing to inform the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency of a medical condition is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions to prosecute in such cases are a matter for the Crown Prosecution Service in England and Wales and the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service in Scotland.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846972/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T12:22:44.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846972/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846972/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people were prosecuted for failing to inform DVLA of medical conditions in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","129146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846973","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>Doctors play an important role in the medical notification process by advising their patients of the effect of any treatment or medication that they are receiving and whether they should notify the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA). The DVLA will often correspond with a patient’s doctor, consultant or optician as part of the medical investigation to determine the impact of the patient’s condition on their fitness to drive. The DVLA provides a dedicated telephone line which allows doctors to discuss concerns about a patient’s fitness to drive with one of the DVLA’s doctors.</p><p> </p><p>A doctor may also decide to notify the DVLA directly about a patient’s medical condition. This is provided for in guidance from the General Medical Council, which states that while doctors must make every reasonable effort to persuade their patients to inform the DVLA, they may themselves notify the DVLA of a patient’s medical condition, in confidence, if the patient does not do so.</p><p> </p><p>To assist the medical profession the DVLA has created a dedicated form that may be used for this purpose. The DVLA treats notifications received from doctors and opticians as a high priority.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846973/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T09:53:04.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846973/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846973/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what provisions are in place to allow doctors to provide information to the DVLA on a person’s fitness to drive.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","129147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846974","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Worsley and Eccles South (Barbara Keeley) on 26 February 2018 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=128962" target="_blank">128962</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846974/answer",,,,,"129411 ; 129493 ; 129653","2018-03-01T14:37:51.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846974/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846974/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Social Services: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate his Department has made of the total sleep-in back pay liability for care providers in Warwick and Leamington constituency.","false","Biography information for Matt Western","Warwick and Leamington","Matt Western","129148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846975","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-01","<p>Land at Long Valley Training area, which includes Eelmoor is unavailable for public recreational use for approximately 320 days each year as a result of military training.</p><p>A breakdown of the 320 days into military training, public safety, security, conservation and the interests of tenants is not recorded separately.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846975/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T15:39:00.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846975/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846975/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-22","Ministry of Defence: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 15 January 2018 to Question 121593, what assessment his Department has made of the proportion of time that Ministry of Defence land near Eelmoor Training Area will be unavailable to the public for recreational purposes as a result of (a) military training, (b) public safety, (c) security, (d) conservation and (e) the interests of tenants on that land.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","129149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846976","Home Office","false","2018-02-27","<p>The Home Office does not hold centrally any information on the number of trained wildlife crime officers.</p><p>It is for elected Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables to decide how their force’s resources are deployed.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846976/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:49:55.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846976/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846976/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-22","Wildlife: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2018 to Question 127241, what information her Department holds on the number of fully trained wildlife crime officers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","129150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846977","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-01","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has approached the hon. Member for Dudley North to offer a visit to the HMRC office in Brierley Hill. I understand he has accepted the offer and will be going there in the next few weeks, where HMRC officials will be on hand to answer his questions.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846977/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T14:49:16.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846977/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846977/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-22","Revenue and Customs: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will meet the hon. Member for Dudley North and representatives of HMRC staff based at the Waterfront in Dudley to discuss the future of their office.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","129151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846978","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-27","<p>Where applicable, obligations concerning the upkeep of roads in common parts of commonhold developments should be set out in a commonhold community statement. This document defines the boundaries of the commonhold units and sets out the rights and obligations of unit holders and the commonhold association.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846978/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-27T17:38:45.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846978/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846978/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-22","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what his Department's policy is on the upkeep of roads in common parts of commonhold housing developments.","false","Biography information for Matt Western","Warwick and Leamington","Matt Western","129152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846979","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>The Government’s and Transport for London’s immediate priority is to see the Crossrail project delivered on time and I am pleased to report that this continues to be the case, with full operations commencing from late 2019.</p><p> </p><p>There are no current plans to extend the Crossrail route and no assessment has been made of the amount or availability of funding for an extension to Basingstoke.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846979/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T10:11:06.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846979/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846979/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Crossrail Line: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 January 2018 to Question 122085 on Crossrail, what assessment his Department has made of the (a) amount and (b) availability of funding required.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","129153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846980","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>There are no current plans to extend the Crossrail route to Basingstoke and no assessment has been made of the technical feasibility to do so.</p><p> </p><p>The Governance for Railway Investment Projects (GRIP) process describes how Network Rail manages and controls projects that enhance or renew the national rail network. GRIP divides a project into eight stages. Options are considered at GRIP stage 2 (Feasibility) which looks at whether they can be delivered economically and in line with current network proposals and strategies. At this stage the preferred option is defined and outline designs are produced. Technical feasibility of an option that has been selected is usually considered in detail in GRIP stage 4, Single Option Development.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846980/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T10:16:22.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846980/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846980/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Crossrail Line: Basingstoke","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 January 2018 to Question 122085 on Crossrail,  what assessment his Department has made of the technical feasibility of extending Crossrail to Basingstoke; and what criteria his Department uses to assess the technical feasibility of such proposals.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","129154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846981","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-28","<p>The most recent NHS Digital workforce statistics (for October 2017) show the number of consultants working in the National Health Service has increased by 28% since May 2010, with numbers at record levels.</p><p> </p><p>The Government currently funds over 6,000 medical school places in England each year. In addition, the Government has also committed to funding 1,500 more medical school places from 2019 at medical schools in England for domestic students to ensure we can train more doctors to meet the future need of our citizens as part of the historic medical expansion.</p><p> </p><p>‘Facing the Facts – Shaping the Future – a draft health and care workforce strategy for England to 2027’ sets out actions being taken to ensure sufficient supply of doctors across all grades and specialties. This includes working with a range of Royal Colleges and provider organisations to identify and support senior medical staff recruitment from European Economic Area (EEA) and non-EEA countries, and reforming postgraduate medical education to better support the development of the doctors of tomorrow.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement provides Health Education England with support which includes looking at geographical variations in the number of doctors per head of population and correlating this to outcomes for selected specialties, and more efficient utilisation of consultants through e-rostering and job planning.</p><p> </p><p>Locally, responsibility for staffing levels, including the consultant workforce, rests with individual NHS trusts and their boards who are best placed to decide how many staff they need to provide a given service.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846981/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-28T14:46:56.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846981/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846981/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Hospitals: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what short-term steps his Department is taking to tackle the shortage of consultants.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","129155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846982","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>The Department for Transport undertakes Cost-Benefit Analysis, using the guidance set out in WebTAG (available at https://www.gov.uk/guidance/transport-analysis-guidance-webtag), to inform enhancement decisions.</p><p> </p><p>This analysis considers the impacts of alternative options to deliver a stated objective, and attempts to quantify them where possible. These impacts include the infrastructure costs of the scheme and the ongoing financial impacts for railway services, as well as the social impacts of the scheme for train users and other affected parties (such as road users and local residents). Wider economic impacts (such as making it easier for people to access more productive jobs) are also considered.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846982/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T10:23:46.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846982/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846982/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Crossrail Line: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 January 2018 to Question 122085 on Crossrail, what criteria his Department uses to assess whether such proposals are good value for money.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","129156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846983","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-01","<p>We have been working closely with the British Plastics Federation and other major stakeholders to promote the sustainability of the plastics industry and encourage its contribution to the circular economy. In the recent Industrial Strategy White Paper we committed to publishing a new UK Bioeconomy Strategy. This will provide a framework within which government, industry and the research community can support the development of bio-based products and processes, including bioplastics.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846983/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T16:09:43.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846983/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846983/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-22","Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential role of bioplastics in replacing non-biodegradable plastics.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846984","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-02","<p>The recently published Mendoza Review of museums in England found that public funding to museums and galleries in England has totalled over £8.4 billion in the past decade. Museums in Cornwall receive public funding from a variety of sources, including Arts Council England (ACE), Heritage Lottery Fund (HLF), local authorities and others, as well as benefiting from a range of tax reliefs and grants. It is therefore not possible to provide a comprehensive breakdown of public funding for museums in the region.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>ACE has invested in Cornwall’s museums through its support for Cornwall Museums Partnership (CMP). As a Major Partnership Museum, CMP has received £1.5m from ACE since 2015, and as a National Portfolio Organisation in the next spending round from 2018-2022 will receive £2.44m funding to enable Cornwall’s museums to become a strong network of sustainable organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Government also directly sponsors Tate St Ives which reopened in October following a major project which saw it nearly double in size, supported by £2.8m from the HLF.</p><p> </p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846984/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T12:53:01.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846984/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846984/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-02-22","Museums and Galleries: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the level of public funding for museums in (a) Cornwall and (b) North Cornwall.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846985","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-28","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of medical practitioners refused a Tier 2 (General) Certificate of Sponsorship centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to monitor and analyse overall staffing levels across the National Health Service and adult social care in addition to trust spending on agency staff. We work across Government to ensure there will continue to be sufficient staff to deliver safe, high quality, efficient services on which patients rely.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846985/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-28T14:48:01.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846985/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846985/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","General Practitioners: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many medical practitioners have been refused a Tier 2 (General) Certificate of Sponsorship since November 2017 due to the annual cap of 20,700; and what assessment he has made of the effect of those refusals on (a) levels of patient-facing activity and (b)  locum costs.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846986","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>Data on the number of diagnoses of cancer in men attributable to human papillomavirus are not collected in the format requested.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846986/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T15:22:49.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846986/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846986/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Cancer: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many diagnoses of cancer in men were attributable to HPV in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846987","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), the expert committee that advises ministers on immunisation related issues, is currently considering the impact and cost-effectiveness of extending the human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccination programme to adolescent boys. This will include an assessment of the effectiveness of HPV vaccines in this group.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2015, JCVI advised an HPV immunisation programme for men who have sex with men, up to and including the age of 45 years, who attend genitourinary medicine and HIV clinics. This was based on an assessment of the impact and cost-effectiveness of a three dose vaccination programme undertaken by Public Health England. Further information can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5404831/pdf/ciw845.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5404831/pdf/ciw845.pdf</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846987/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T15:25:55.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846987/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846987/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of potential effectiveness of a HPV vaccination programme for men.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846988","Department for Education","false","2018-03-02","<p>The government funds 15 hours of free childcare a week for disadvantaged children aged two, three and four, as well as the early years pupil premium for disadvantaged three and four year olds.</p><p> </p><p>Early years funding is allocated on a local authority basis and Cornwall’s funding allocations for the following financial years can be found at the following links:</p><p><br> 2018/19 (Initial allocation): <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019</a>.</p><p> </p><p>2017/18 (Provisional allocation): <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/<br> dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846988/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T14:52:45.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846988/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846988/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-22","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much his Department plans to spend on childcare for disadvantaged children in 2018 in (a) Cornwall and (b) North Cornwall.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846989","Department for Education","false","2018-03-02","<p>Allocations for students studying at post-16 institutions are not available separately for students aged 16 and 17, although data on allocations and student numbers are available for 16 to 19 year olds as set out in published allocations data. The following allocations show the average funding per student in England, Cornwall and North Cornwall for the last five academic years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Average funding per student</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017/18</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>£4,685</p></td><td><p>£4,586</p></td><td><p>£4,639</p></td><td><p>£4,625</p></td><td><p>£4,625</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cornwall</p></td><td><p>£4,389</p></td><td><p>£4,355</p></td><td><p>£4,480</p></td><td><p>£4,541</p></td><td><p>£4,554</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North Cornwall</p></td><td><p>£4,157</p></td><td><p>£4,140</p></td><td><p>£4,281</p></td><td><p>£4,258</p></td><td><p>£4,267</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The above figures exclude high needs funding but include both full and part-time students, and allocations for the 16 to 19 bursary fund and free meals funding.</p><p>Institutions in Cornwall and North Cornwall are funded through the same national funding formula as the rest of England and have received the same £4,000 base rate of funding for full time 16 and 17 year olds throughout the period. Average funding per student in Cornwall and North Cornwall is lower due to other factors in the 16 to 19 funding formula, for example, institutions in Cornwall do not attract an area cost uplift for higher delivery costs like those in London and South East England.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846989/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T14:47:52.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846989/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846989/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-22","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much has been allocated from the public purse for 16 and 17-year olds studying in further education per capita in (a) England, (b) Cornwall and (c) North Cornwall in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846990","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The prevalence of childhood obesity in Cornwall (including Isles of Scilly) for academic year 2016/17 for reception age children (aged four to five years) is 10.0%.</p><p> </p><p>The prevalence of childhood obesity in Cornwall (including Isles of Scilly) for academic year 2016/17 for Year Six age children (aged 10-11 years) is 15.1%.</p><p> </p><p>The data are publicly available on the Public Health England fingertips tool here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/national-child-measurement-programme/data#page/0/gid/8000011/pat/6/par/E12000009/ati/102/are/E06000052" target="_blank">https://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/national-child-measurement-programme/data#page/0/gid/8000011/pat/6/par/E12000009/ati/102/are/E06000052</a></p><p> </p><p>Prevalence rates for childhood obesity for children at other ages are not collected in large enough samples to generate reliable county-level data.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846990/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-01T15:21:58.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846990/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846990/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the childhood obesity rate is in Cornwall.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846991","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-28","<p>Figures for additional affordable housing units supplied are published in live table 1008C <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-affordable-housing-supply" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-affordable-housing-supply</a></p><p>Figures are published at local authority level, since 2009-10 figures are only available at Cornwall unitary authority level.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846991/answer",,,,,,"2018-02-28T16:59:43.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846991/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846991/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-22","Affordable Housing: North Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many affordable housing units have been completed in North Cornwall in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846992","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-02","<p>The number of fines imposed by courts for speeding offences in the Cornwall Local Justice area, from 2015 to 2016 (latest available data), can be viewed in the table. Data for courts specifically located in North Cornwall cannot be separately identified.</p><p> </p><p>Court proceedings data for 2017 are planned for publication in May 2018.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846992/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T14:55:12.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846992/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846992/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-22","Speed Limits: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people received speeding fines in North Cornwall in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846993","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-02","<p>The Bus Services Operators Grant (BSOG) is a demand-led grant regime in England under which payments are made to bus companies to help meet some of their fuel costs in running local bus services. BSOG spend figures are published annually on Gov.uk and can be found via this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bus-services-grants-and-funding#bsog-spend" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bus-services-grants-and-funding#bsog-spend</a></p><p> </p><p>BSOG spend figures are broken down to upper tier local authority level only, and not further to North Cornwall, specifically.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that the local authorities listed in the table are derived from the address given on the BSOG claim form. This means that the figures do <em>not</em> reflect the geographical location of bus services, and may not capture all relevant services in Cornwall.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of claims received in the Department that are clearly identified as being located from operators in Cornwall, a total of £1,031,489.59 was paid in 2014-15, £76,363.15 in 2015-2016, and £75,977.93 in 2016-17. Note that the reason for the big drop in BSOG paid after 2014/15 is due to a bus company with an address in Cornwall ceasing trading. Whilst their services were absorbed by other operators, the addresses on the claim forms for these other operators were outside Cornwall therefore spend has been attributed to other upper tier local authorities.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846993/answer",,,,,,"2018-03-02T10:42:50.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846993/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846993/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-22","Bus Services: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to the public purse has been of subsidising bus travel in (a) Cornwall and (b) North Cornwall in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","129167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846994","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The information requested is shown in the following tables:</p><p> </p><p>Value of new loans issued to National Health Service providers:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£4,151,961,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£3,777,273,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£942,724,189</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£580,678,218</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£379,989,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£409,063,125</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£552,101,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>£442,461,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>£359,071,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>£108,265,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Total amount of loan repayments and interest received:</p><p>Loan repayments</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£1,312,676,281</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£1,423,203,805</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£235,682,193</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£182,828,547</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£243,000,334</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£178,943,605</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£202,757,139</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>£198,542,221</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>£282,616,045</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>£223,385,871</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Interest received</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£161,036,265</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£106,055,536</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£72,355,773</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£62,903,714</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£58,682,866</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£55,93